The wealth of typical Australian savers is in surprisingly robust shape after a traumatic year for their personal and financial health provided they did not panic and convert savings to cash in the depths of the market sell-off. The average superannuation fund is on track to end 2020 up 3.2 per cent, more than making up for eyewatering losses in February and March, figures from research house Rainmaker show. Residential real estate prices have risen 1.8 per cent in aggregate from the start of the year, led by Adelaide with a 5.6 per cent increase, CoreLogic figures to the first three weeks of December show. Melbourne worst hit by COVID-19 lags the pack with a 1.7 per cent decline. With the share market also set for a modest rise, the three pillars of Australian savings are all set to end the year in the black just. Alex Dunnin, Rainmaker's head of research, said the turnaround was a "remarkable outcome" after the February-March crash and demonstrated the superannuation industry was doing a good job of safeguarding Australians' retirement savings. He said the S&P/ASX 200 Index was set to finish up 2.8 per cent, meaning super funds had on average outperformed the index by 40 basis points."While this is way down on the 14.9 per cent calendar year return for 2019, given whats gone on through the year, its a remarkable outcome," he said. "This means that MySuper funds, on average, have now fully recovered all the losses they suffered in the February-March COVID-19 financial correction. The 3.2 per cent index return is also way ahead of inflation, implying most funds beat their investment objectives. Again, given what happened during the year, [it's] another remarkable result," he said. Rainmaker's MySuper index tracks the performance of superannuation funds' default MySuper products, which employer contributions are automatically paid into unless a member actively picks another option. This year's projected 3.2 per cent return is dramatically down on 2019, when the Rainmaker MySuper index ended up 14.9 per cent. But it was a good result in the context of the 27 per cent loss on the benchmark share index in February and March, when pandemic fears sent global markets into a nosedive. This year's final result will be better than 2018, when super funds ended the year exactly where they started. Over the last five years, the MySuper index has returned an average of 7.1 per cent, with 7 per cent for 2016, 10.4 per cent for 2017, 0 per cent for 2018, 14.9 per cent for 2019 and a projected 3.2 per cent for 2020. By contrast, in the last five years, the S&P/ASX 200 Index has returned an average of 9.4 per cent, meaning MySuper options have underperformed Australian equities. Mr Dunnin said that was "as it should be" because MySuper options were designed to sacrifice upside for protection against the downside. He pointed out that as the ASX 200 fell 27 per cent in March, the MySuper index only dropped 13 per cent. "These results mean that super funds have pretty much done just as their fund members would have expected: stay the course, not panic, and position themselves so they can reap the gains when markets bounce back," he said. But he added the story with super funds' international share portfolios was not "not so shiny". "In international shares, apart from a few really sharp super funds, super funds generally struggle to match the index." Geoff Wilson, chairman and chief investment officer of fund manager Wilson Asset Management, said all his actively managed funds had beaten their benchmarks this year, demonstrating that 2020 was a year in which active management proved its value. This year has been a year for active managers. The market hasnt been going up in a straight line. Theres been skill [in picking the good companies]. "The big decision for most fund managers this year ... was how to reposition your portfolio so it would be exposed to the companies that would benefit from the new normal." He said this was something passive index trackers could not do. As of December 23, he said WAM Capital beat its benchmark by 6.1 per cent, WAM Microcap by 16.4 per cent, WAM Leaders by 3.9 per cent and WAM Global by 4.8 per cent.

There is a lack of harmonisation in terms of how it applies, and a lack of standards that might underpin the collation and disclosure of data. This provides ample scope for corporate virtue signalling, also known as green-washing, in the context of climate. To address this, in late 2015 the Financial Stability Board, under the leadership of Mark Carney, established the Task Force of Climate-related Financial Disclosure. With Michael Bloomberg as chairman, the TCFD has pushed for reliable climate-related financial disclosure, structured under four thematics: governance, strategy, risk management, and metrics and targets. As of last September, more than 1500 organisations support the TCFD, nearly doubling from the year prior, and representing a market capitalisation of $US12.6 trillion ($16.4 trillion). In the public arena, the TCFD has also found strong support. In September, New Zealand became the first country in the world to signal its intention to mandate climate-related financial disclosure. The accompanying statement confirmed that this would be based on the TCFDs recommendations, and would apply across all listed companies, as well as the financial sector (asset owners, insurers and banks). Rishi Sunak, Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer, followed this up in November, committing to TCFD becoming mandatory by 2025 for the UK. Hong Kong did likewise in December and other countries are expected to follow this year. Against this backdrop, a wonkish yet very important development occurred in late September 2020. The IFRS Foundation, the peak body for international financial reporting standards, issued its Consultation Paper on Sustainability Reporting. The thrust of this initiative was to secure support for the foundation to assume a global leadership position in sustainability reporting, and to drive the development and adoption of standards. This is no small task. But it is happening. And it is very likely to involve the establishment of a Sustainability Standards Board, similar to the International Accounting Standards Board, which develops standards on behalf of the foundation for global adoption. (IFRS Standards are used for all or most domestic-listed companies and financial institutions in 144 countries.) Critically, the foundations proposal secured the joint and same-day support from the five organisations that have paved the way on sustainability standard-setting since the early 2000s, namely CDP, Climate Disclosure Standards Board, Global Reporting Initiative, International Integrated Reporting Council and Sustainability Accounting Standards Board. This group of five then took a further step in December, issuing a prototypical climate-related reporting standard. This is an enormously far-reaching document. It introduces two new layers of accountability, namely sustainability reporting and sustainability-related financial disclosure, to complement traditional financial reporting. In doing so, it aligns corporate reporting with sustainable development, and thereby transforms the bedrock concept of enterprise value. This framework also has profound implications for governance, including in terms of incentivising sustainability within corporate structures, and in mandating third-party assurance. The pursuit of harmonisation will also enable the formation of new and large-scale data sets that will inevitably come to be reflected in the pricing of financial instruments. There is a long journey ahead, but make no mistake, these developments represent a new era of stakeholder-driven capitalism. For Australia, the foundations proposal received support from the Financial Reporting Council, the Australian Accounting Standards Board and the Auditing and Assurance Standards Board in a joint submission in December. The submission emphasised the need to secure upfront support from governments and established organisations in order to mitigate the risk of merely adding to the current complexity in reporting. There is also strong leadership being shown by many C-suites, and by institutional investors, most notably the Investor Group of Climate Change, whose members account for more than $2 trillion in funds under management. The high-profile lawsuit that Rest Super settled late last year also acted as an ESG (environmental, social and governance) catalyst for superannuation trustees, and further debate around the scope of the sole purpose test. Still, as with most aspects of Australias policies on climate, there is the question of leadership from Canberra. And with the Treasurer supporting an inquiry by the joint standing committee on trade and investment growth into the de-banking of coal, the portents are not good. The shame of this it not limited to Australia swimming against an inevitable global tide (which will include the US from January 20). It is that we are forgoing opportunities in reshaping Australia, and capitalism writ large.

London | Struggling luxury car brand Jaguar will be fully electric by 2025, the British company said on Monday (Tuesday) as it outlined a plan to phase out internal combustion engines. Jaguar Land Rover, which is owned by Indian conglomerate Tata Motors, hopes the move will help turn around the fortunes of the 86-year-old Jaguar brand, which for many epitomises class but has struggled in recent years. The switch to an electric future will involve moving car production from JLRs Castle Bromwich factory east of the central England city of Birmingham to nearby Solihull. Chief executive Thierry Bollore said the firm was exploring opportunities to repurpose the Castle Bromwich plant, leading to speculation it could be used for battery production. Jaguar Land Rover also said that the far more profitable Land Rover brand will produce its first all-electric model in 2024 as it, too, phases out internal combustion engines.We have all the ingredients at our disposal to reimagine the business and the experiences our customers seek, to reimagine to benchmark of luxury, Mr Bollore said. The move was welcomed by British Transport Secretary Grant Shapps as a huge step for British car manufacturing. The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders, the British car industrys lobby group, said the announcement represented an injection of confidence into the sector, which has suffered over the past year during the coronavirus pandemic. The wealth of typical Australian savers is in surprisingly robust shape after a traumatic year for their personal and financial health provided they did not panic and convert savings to cash in the depths of the market sell-off. The average superannuation fund is on track to end 2020 up 3.2 per cent, more than making up for eyewatering losses in February and March, figures from research house Rainmaker show. Residential real estate prices have risen 1.8 per cent in aggregate from the start of the year, led by Adelaide with a 5.6 per cent increase, CoreLogic figures to the first three weeks of December show. Melbourne worst hit by COVID-19 lags the pack with a 1.7 per cent decline. With the share market also set for a modest rise, the three pillars of Australian savings are all set to end the year in the black just. Alex Dunnin, Rainmaker's head of research, said the turnaround was a "remarkable outcome" after the February-March crash and demonstrated the superannuation industry was doing a good job of safeguarding Australians' retirement savings. He said the S&P/ASX 200 Index was set to finish up 2.8 per cent, meaning super funds had on average outperformed the index by 40 basis points."While this is way down on the 14.9 per cent calendar year return for 2019, given whats gone on through the year, its a remarkable outcome," he said. "This means that MySuper funds, on average, have now fully recovered all the losses they suffered in the February-March COVID-19 financial correction. The 3.2 per cent index return is also way ahead of inflation, implying most funds beat their investment objectives. Again, given what happened during the year, [it's] another remarkable result," he said. Rainmaker's MySuper index tracks the performance of superannuation funds' default MySuper products, which employer contributions are automatically paid into unless a member actively picks another option. This year's projected 3.2 per cent return is dramatically down on 2019, when the Rainmaker MySuper index ended up 14.9 per cent. But it was a good result in the context of the 27 per cent loss on the benchmark share index in February and March, when pandemic fears sent global markets into a nosedive. This year's final result will be better than 2018, when super funds ended the year exactly where they started. Over the last five years, the MySuper index has returned an average of 7.1 per cent, with 7 per cent for 2016, 10.4 per cent for 2017, 0 per cent for 2018, 14.9 per cent for 2019 and a projected 3.2 per cent for 2020. By contrast, in the last five years, the S&P/ASX 200 Index has returned an average of 9.4 per cent, meaning MySuper options have underperformed Australian equities. Mr Dunnin said that was "as it should be" because MySuper options were designed to sacrifice upside for protection against the downside. He pointed out that as the ASX 200 fell 27 per cent in March, the MySuper index only dropped 13 per cent. But he added the story with super funds' international share portfolios was not "not so shiny". "In international shares, apart from a few really sharp super funds, super funds generally struggle to match the index." "The big decision for most fund managers this year ... was how to reposition your portfolio so it would be exposed to the companies that would benefit from the new normal." He said this was something passive index trackers could not do. There is a lack of harmonisation in terms of how it applies, and a lack of standards that might underpin the collation and disclosure of data. This provides ample scope for corporate virtue signalling, also known as green-washing, in the context of climate. To address this, in late 2015 the Financial Stability Board, under the leadership of Mark Carney, established the Task Force of Climate-related Financial Disclosure. With Michael Bloomberg as chairman, the TCFD has pushed for reliable climate-related financial disclosure, structured under four thematics: governance, strategy, risk management, and metrics and targets. As of last September, more than 1500 organisations support the TCFD, nearly doubling from the year prior, and representing a market capitalisation of $US12.6 trillion ($16.4 trillion). In the public arena, the TCFD has also found strong support. In September, New Zealand became the first country in the world to signal its intention to mandate climate-related financial disclosure. The accompanying statement confirmed that this would be based on the TCFDs recommendations, and would apply across all listed companies, as well as the financial sector (asset owners, insurers and banks). Rishi Sunak, Britain's Chancellor of the Exchequer, followed this up in November, committing to TCFD becoming mandatory by 2025 for the UK. Hong Kong did likewise in December and other countries are expected to follow this year. Against this backdrop, a wonkish yet very important development occurred in late September 2020. The IFRS Foundation, the peak body for international financial reporting standards, issued its Consultation Paper on Sustainability Reporting. The thrust of this initiative was to secure support for the foundation to assume a global leadership position in sustainability reporting, and to drive the development and adoption of standards. This is no small task. But it is happening. And it is very likely to involve the establishment of a Sustainability Standards Board, similar to the International Accounting Standards Board, which develops standards on behalf of the foundation for global adoption. (IFRS Standards are used for all or most domestic-listed companies and financial institutions in 144 countries.) Critically, the foundations proposal secured the joint and same-day support from the five organisations that have paved the way on sustainability standard-setting since the early 2000s, namely CDP, Climate Disclosure Standards Board, Global Reporting Initiative, International Integrated Reporting Council and Sustainability Accounting Standards Board. This group of five then took a further step in December, issuing a prototypical climate-related reporting standard. This is an enormously far-reaching document. It introduces two new layers of accountability, namely sustainability reporting and sustainability-related financial disclosure, to complement traditional financial reporting. In doing so, it aligns corporate reporting with sustainable development, and thereby transforms the bedrock concept of enterprise value. This framework also has profound implications for governance, including in terms of incentivising sustainability within corporate structures, and in mandating third-party assurance. The pursuit of harmonisation will also enable the formation of new and large-scale data sets that will inevitably come to be reflected in the pricing of financial instruments. There is a long journey ahead, but make no mistake, these developments represent a new era of stakeholder-driven capitalism. For Australia, the foundations proposal received support from the Financial Reporting Council, the Australian Accounting Standards Board and the Auditing and Assurance Standards Board in a joint submission in December. The submission emphasised the need to secure upfront support from governments and established organisations in order to mitigate the risk of merely adding to the current complexity in reporting. There is also strong leadership being shown by many C-suites, and by institutional investors, most notably the Investor Group of Climate Change, whose members account for more than $2 trillion in funds under management. The high-profile lawsuit that Rest Super settled late last year also acted as an ESG (environmental, social and governance) catalyst for superannuation trustees, and further debate around the scope of the sole purpose test. Still, as with most aspects of Australias policies on climate, there is the question of leadership from Canberra. And with the Treasurer supporting an inquiry by the joint standing committee on trade and investment growth into the de-banking of coal, the portents are not good. The shame of this it not limited to Australia swimming against an inevitable global tide (which will include the US from January 20). It is that we are forgoing opportunities in reshaping Australia, and capitalism writ large. 3 < 0.1%

Like all good story tips this one was delivered over a beer. It was late 2019 and Id just spoken on a white-collar crime panel with an academic friend of mine, Clinton Free, from Sydney University. The Sure Thing is six episodes of true crime, charting how two university friends hatched a near perfect plan to commit modest, under-the-radar insider trading. They bought burner phones, limited their contact and agreed to only profit $200,000. But greed and betrayal would mark this endeavour from the very beginning. One of the offenders would eventually make $7.8 million, the other just $20,000. After months of struggling to catch this pair of amateurs, the Australian Federal Police and the Australian Securities and Investments Commission arrested Lukas Kamay and Chris Hill in May 2014. Jail and all its brutality was now the only certainty in their lives. The podcast contemplates the culture of risk-taking by young men, the worshipping of money on trading floors and if a second chance is possible for white collar criminals. International travel restrictions put in place to limit the spread of COVID-19 have cut off a key source of professionals for the big four consulting firms, leaving them scrambling to hire experienced accountants and consultants. Like all global professional services firms, the big four typically have an ongoing influx of professionals from their overseas branches brought into the country to work on client projects. But this supply of staff has been severely curtailed by COVID-19-related travel restrictions into the country. The lower number of available foreign professionals, along with growing client demand, has led to a jobs market for experienced advisory professionals described by one recruiter as manic. Pearson's r

The Pearson's correlation coefficient (r) is a measure of linear correlation between two variables. It's value lies between -1 and +1, -1 indicating total negative linear correlation, 0 indicating no linear correlation and 1 indicating total positive linear correlation. Furthermore, r is invariant under separate changes in location and scale of the two variables, implying that for a linear function the angle to the x-axis does not affect r.

To calculate r for two variables X and Y, one divides the covariance of X and Y by the product of their standard deviations.

Spearman's

The Spearman's rank correlation coefficient () is a measure of monotonic correlation between two variables, and is therefore better in catching nonlinear monotonic correlations than Pearson's r. It's value lies between -1 and +1, -1 indicating total negative monotonic correlation, 0 indicating no monotonic correlation and 1 indicating total positive monotonic correlation.

To calculate for two variables X and Y, one divides the covariance of the rank variables of X and Y by the product of their standard deviations.

Kendall's

Similarly to Spearman's rank correlation coefficient, the Kendall rank correlation coefficient () measures ordinal association between two variables. It's value lies between -1 and +1, -1 indicating total negative correlation, 0 indicating no correlation and 1 indicating total positive correlation.

To calculate for two variables X and Y, one determines the number of concordant and discordant pairs of observations. is given by the number of concordant pairs minus the discordant pairs divided by the total number of pairs.

MalikMagnetic sun storms could hold the secret to gas pricesIf you want to know where natural gas prices are heading, maybe it's time to check out the sun. Magnetic storms on its surface can generate dark-looking areas called sunspots, blemishes that wax and wane in roughly 11-year cycles and may hold clues for predicting weather patterns: The fewer the spots, the colder winter will be in swaths of the Northern Hemisphere. That's the theory, anyway, and one that's gaining ground among commercial meteorologists on the lookout for new ways to serve their clients traders eager to know how cold it's going to be so they can gauge natural-gas demand. "I was a real sceptic on the impact of solar cycles and sunspots,'' said Todd Crawford, senior meteorological scientist at IBM's The Weather Co. But after studying the patterns of cold winters that followed the last low point in the cycle, "I was on board." To understand it, think of the sun's magnetic field as a sort of umbrella for Earth, said Scott McIntosh, director of the High Altitude Observatory at the National Centre for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colorado. The umbrella can block some cosmic rays charged particles from long-dead stars from bombarding the atmosphere.When fewer sunspots form, the field weakens and more rays get through to hit Earth. Then the chances go up that frigid air dropping out of the Arctic, as it often does during winter, will get trapped in eastern North America or Europe and bring on harsh episodes of shiver-inducing weather, said Matt Rogers, president of the Commodity Weather Group. Not everyone in the meteorological world is sold on the spots' predictive power when it comes to terrestrial weather. They're somewhat controversial, too, because they play a role in a theory that some climate-change deniers have latched onto about how global warming isn't a threat; pretty soon a chilling sunspot cycle will come to the rescue, these folks contend, and cool things down on Earth. McIntosh, an astrophysicist, said he believes the sunspots do affect Earth's weather. Though he thinks more research is needed, he won't argue with the meteorologists, and if it turns out he is wrong, "I'm prepared to be hung in effigy." The sun right now is in a blemish-free period, known as a solar minimum. The last one occurred around 2009 when cosmic rays began hitting Earth at the highest levels in records going back to 1964 at the University of Oulu's cosmic ray station at the Sodankyla Geophysical Observatory in Finland. The current low-point in the cycle is "aiming to be even quieter than the previous one,'' said Rogers of Commodity Weather Group. A looming El Nino in the Pacific is already pointing to a stormy US winter that could get a boost from the solar minimum, said IBM's Crawford, which could mean "higher than normal snowfall through all the major eastern US cities, especially at the end of winter." The market seems to be suspecting as much. Natural-gas futures rallied 41 per cent in November, the biggest November gain since 2000. Gas stockpiles are at a 16-year seasonal low as the heating season kicks off. John Kilduff, partner at Again Capital in New York, said he's willing to give the sunspot-weather theory consideration. "With all energy markets, you have to expose yourself with things outside your lane," he said. "Apparently this is a significant enough development that we have to pay attention." Bloomberg

The day before a bombshell story had dropped that alleged Amazons use of preferential treatment in favour of large retailers on their platform in India, including two companies where beneficial interests were held. The displacement of brick and mortar businesses in India has long been a vulnerability for Modi, owing to his core constituency of Hindu nationalists. The story was the equivalent of lobbing a grenade, and at the same time an illustration of how important investigatory journalism is to modern democracies. Facebooks Australian news ban was handed down from Palo Alto shortly thereafter, at 5.30am AEDT, to be precise. It is important to emphasise that as a listed US company, rather than a public utility, Facebook had every right to do what it did.But the execution was as culturally inept as it was reprehensible. Fair warning ought to have been provided, rather than utilising real-time PSYOP tactics on the institutions that comprise the civil society of an allied country. The backtracking on Saturday was mealy-mouthed, as well. Facebook had plenty of time to give due consideration to implementation, as this step had been threatened as far back as late August. They could have also run small scale beta tests, including as a warning to those reliant on their platform, as Google did with its search algorithm in mid-January. For good measure, the UK Supreme Court ruled against Uber late on Friday, settling a long-running dispute, in favour of drivers being designated as workers rather than self-employed entrepreneurs. This sets up broad ranging liability, in terms of minimum wage and employee benefits, and may have implications in other jurisdictions as well. Maybe Prime Minister Johnston can join a three-way call next time around, using Signal ideally. These are not isolated incidents. They reflect the rise and rise of centralised technology platforms, that have fundamentally disrupted the real economy, for better, and also for worse. The problem is not the innovation itself, nor the benefits that have been provided to consumers, and to digitally savvy vendors too. It is that the platforms continue to prioritise the interests of shareholders, rather than a broader concept of stakeholders. The result is what we are seeing: the creation of a class of tech oligarchs, a collapse of social sustainability, ever more aggressive tactics in terms of tax minimisation (including locally by gamifying research and developments credits), and broader forms of regulatory and jurisdictional arbitrage. If this was not enough, the vast power that accrues to big tech through big data collation and algorithmic search and ranking, bring it further into conflict with governments, in terms of who controls the commanding heights of the digital economy. The ability to de-platform individuals and institutions also provides a form of coercive control that can shape the national discourse, as we saw last month in the US. For Facebook specifically, the rejoinder from a broad swathe of Silicon Valley is that the Morrison government has no business in supporting and subsidising a legacy business model, in the form of mainstream media, which itself is conflicted given the patronage it provides to specific political parties. Additionally, they argue that social media has provided a means by which smaller and more diverse voices can amplify their message. The first contention does not hold up. Media is different from an auto plant or a coal mine. It is the fourth estate, and provides a critical public service in liberal societies, acting as both as a check and a balance. In Australia, the ACCC highlighted in its final report of the Digital Platforms Inquiry in 2019 that advertising revenues had collapsed in the 15 years to 2016 from $3.7 billion to $225 million when adjusted for inflation. While paywalls have provided an offset, the rotation to online advertising, that is now dominated by Facebook and Google (in the ballpark of 81 per cent), has undercut all forms of print media in Australia. A carefully calibrated legislative intervention is required on this basis alone, and categorically deserves the cross-party support is has received. The second contention is much stronger, and is well illustrated by what happened on Thursday. But Facebook cannot have its cake and eat it. It is either here to support civic engagement and social networking, or it can and should exit the stage, so that others can proliferate and be relied upon to provide services to a broader set of stakeholders. It is important, as well, not to view this as an episode in time. The trends in favour of machine learning, artificial intelligence, automation, robotics, augmented and virtual reality, cyber-physical systems and so forth, are inexorable and accelerating. As this new era impends, the right questions need to be asked. As far as technology goes, the best exposition we have seen is from the 3Ai Institute at the Australian National University. The three As stand autonomy, agency and assurance, in terms of how we, as humans, interact and retain governance over the technology of the future. These topics will, in time, make our Facebook moment look like a minor conflagration. In the meantime, we need to get on with it. And there are different perspectives and modalities in play. In our view, the end game is not utopian crypto projects, even if they are crossing the Rubicon. Crypto maximalists are preaching decentralisation, whilst enriching and empowering themselves, and breaking with the social contract that has underpinned liberal societies since the 17th century. Nor does the solution lie in China, which is heading in the opposite direction via its central bank digital currency. This will ultimately form a key component of Chinas surveillance apparatus, and is a fundamentally illiberal project. The middle ground is to acknowledge and embrace democracy for all its flaws, and to shift capitalism away from a narrow focus of shareholder value creation, and toward a broader concept of stakeholders, and sustainability more generally. This is happening, and with a climate-first focus, but the progress is too slow. To bridge the gap democratic governments around the world need to realign and cooperate against the various insurgencies. It is in this context that we view the Digital Platforms Mandatory Bargaining Code as a profoundly important legislative initiative, that all Australians should support.

217602021-02-21 13:14:00+00:002021-02-21 02:24:002021-02-21 13:24:00+00:00-0.298Gig economy, Uber, US Supreme Court, UK, USA, Sadiq Khan, France, Germany, Italy, SpainCompaniesTransportAdam SatarianoUbers UK defeat could be body blow to gig economyGig economyLondon | Ubers defeat in Britain on Friday (Saturday AEDT), where the Supreme Court ruled that drivers are entitled to worker rights, was a major victory for labour activists in Australia, the United States and Europe who are pushing for better wages and stronger protections for gig economy workers. The courts decision, the latest in a string of confrontations between labour groups and gig economy companies in courtrooms and parliaments around the world, poses an existential threat to Uber and other companies that rely on a sprawling labour force of independent contractors to provide car rides, deliver food and clean homes. A group of drivers in Britain, one of Ubers most important markets, won the right to be classified as workers entitled to a minimum wage and vacation time in a decision that could threaten the future of the already unprofitable company. The Supreme Court justices ruled unanimously that although Uber said it was only a technology platform that connected drivers with passengers, it behaved more like an employer by setting rates, assigning rides, requiring drivers to follow certain routes and using a rating system to discipline them. It was a considerable setback for Uber, which had been able to beat back other attempts at forcing it to change how it treats its drivers, including the defeat in November of a California law that would have forced gig companies to make changes similar to those now being forced by the British court ruling.As fast as they have become a part of everyday life and have been valued on Wall Street in the tens of billions of dollars, gig economy companies operate on precarious business models. More often than not, they lose money on every ride offered and every delivery made. In 2020, for example, Uber reported a net loss of $US6.8 billion ($8.6 billion). The British ruling could be a nightmare for Uber if it increases its labour costs, said Daniel Ives, an analyst with Wedbush Securities. London was one of Ubers top five markets globally, he said. This case could set a precedent for other workers and companies in the gig economy throughout the UK and Europe, which would be a body blow to the overall ecosystem, Mr Ives said in a note to clients. Uber and other gig-economy companies have been fighting off efforts around the world to classify workers as employees, with mixed success. In France, Uber lost a decision in the countrys top court last year that a driver had the right to be considered an employee. In Germany, Italy and Spain, disputes about Ubers labour practices have also raised alarms, especially within traditional taxi businesses, limiting its availability. But in California, Uber and other companies funded a successful ballot measure in the November election to exempt them from a law that would have required them to employ drivers and pay health care, unemployment insurance and other benefits. More battles loom in Washington and state capitals about how to classify workers for Uber and other platforms. While Britain has been one of the companys most important markets, it has also been a source of legal trouble. In London, where Uber cars are as ubiquitous as traditional black cabs, the city transportation regulator has twice taken steps to revoke Ubers taxi licence in recent years before the company agreed to new safety policies. Sadiq Khan, mayor of London, cheered the decision. It is a landmark decision for people who suffer from low pay and a lack of security at work, he said in a statement. Gig economy workers deserve the same rights as other workers. Uber fought the effort by drivers in Britain to be classified as workers for the past five years, appealing the decision all the way to the countrys top court. The ruling is expected to initially affect only the 25 drivers who brought the case but is seen as setting a precedent for the 60,000 other Uber drivers across the country. The ruling will now be referred to an employment tribunal, an administrative court that will decide in the next few months how to reward the drivers and how the ruling will affect other drivers. Uber sought to play down the decision, saying it would press the employment tribunal to limit its scope. The company said it believed the ruling should affect only a small number of drivers and that Uber should not be required to reclassify all its drivers as workers. The company said it would argue to the tribunal that it had made a number of changes to its business model to provide more protections for workers since 2016, when the case was filed, like offering insurance to drivers if they lose income because they are sick or injured, and allowing drivers to reject taking certain rides without punishment. We are committed to doing more and will now consult with every active driver across the UK to understand the changes they want to see, Jamie Heywood, Ubers regional general manager for Northern and Eastern Europe, said in a statement. But some employment lawyers said the decision had broader consequences than Uber was suggesting and was an important moment in the broader labour debate about gig workers. The case had much wider implications than the Uber case alone and is likely to be seen as a watershed moment in employment rights for workers in the gig economy, said Schona Jolly, a human rights and employment law barrister with Cloisters Chambers in London. Uber and other gig economy companies say their business model gives people flexibility to choose when they work, while critics say it has eroded job protections and the traditional company-employee relationship. Uber drivers are paid per ride, with Uber taking a 20 per cent fee from each fare. The court said drivers, who must pay for their own car, insurance and taxi licence, are entitled to be paid when they are logged in to the app, not just when they are providing a ride, with some restrictions. In Britain, workers are classified in one of three categories: self-employed with few protections; workers entitled to a minimum wage and some paid time off; and employees with more rights like not to be unfairly fired. The justices criticised the legal agreements that Uber requires drivers to sign before working that classifies them as self-employed. The court said Uber did not have the power to determine for itself whether or not worker protection laws applied to its drivers. Drivers are in a position of subordination and dependency in relation to Uber such that they have little or no ability to improve their economic position through professional or entrepreneurial skill, Lord George Leggatt of the Supreme Court said in reading the judgment. In practice, the only way in which they can increase their earnings is by working longer hours while constantly meeting Ubers measures of performance. Uber said it would send a survey to drivers Saturday to measure their views on the ruling and worker flexibility, to better gauge how to adjust their model to conform to the ruling. As the case plays out in the employment tribunal, Uber may rely on the appeal of gig work for some people the ability to work as much as or as little they like. The New York Times
